http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A related resource that is supplanted, displaced, or superseded by the described resource.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A related resource that is required by the described resource to support its function, delivery, or coherence.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Typically, rights information includes a statement about various property rights associated with the resource, including intellectual property rights.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Information about rights held in and over the resource.
A person or organization owning or managing rights over the resource.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The described resource may be derived from the related resource in whole or in part. Recommended best practice is to identify the related resource by means of a string conforming to a formal identification system.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A related resource from which the described resource is derived.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Spatial characteristics of the resource.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Typically, the subject will be represented using keywords, key phrases, or classification codes. Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The topic of the resource.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A list of subunits of the resource.
Temporal characteristics of the resource.
A name given to the resource.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the DCMI Type Vocabulary [DCMITYPE]. To describe the file format, physical medium, or dimensions of the resource, use the Format element.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The nature or genre of the resource.
Date (often a range) of validity of a resource.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The Data Quality Vocabulary (DQV) is seen as an extension to DCAT to cover the quality of the data, how frequently is it updated, whether it accepts user corrections, persistence commitments etc. When used by publishers, this vocabulary will foster trust in the data amongst developers.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Represents a group of quality dimensions in which a common type of information is used as quality indicator.
Represents criteria relevant for assessing quality. Each quality dimension must have one or more metric to measure it. A dimension is linked with a category using the dqv:inCategory property.
Represents a standard to measure a quality dimension. An observation (instance of dqv:QualityMeasurement) assigns a value in a given unit to a Metric.

Represents quality annotations, including ratings, quality certificates or feedback that can be associated to datasets or distributions. Quality annotations must have one oa:motivatedBy statement with an instance of oa:Motivation (and skos:Concept) that reflects a quality assessment purpose. We define this instance as dqv:qualityAssessment.

An annotation that associates a resource (especially, a dataset or a distribution) to another resource (for example, a document) that certifies the resource's quality according to a set of quality assessment rules.

http://purl.org/vocab/vann/usageNote.@value: The unit of measure in quality measurement should be specified through the property sdmx-attribute:unitMeasure as recommended by RDF Data Cube. The Ontology of units of Measure (OM) by Rijgersberg Et Al provides a list of HTTP dereferenceable unit of measures, which can be exploited as values for sdmx-attribute:unitMeasure.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Represents the evaluation of a given dataset (or dataset distribution) against a specific quality metric.
Represents a dataset of quality measurements, evaluations of one or more datasets (or dataset distributions) against specific quality metrics.

http://purl.org/vocab/vann/usageNote.@value: QualityMetadata containers do not necessary include all types of quality statements DQV can support. Implementers decide the granularity of containment. In the current version of DQV, we also leave open the choice of the containment technique. Implementers can use (RDF) graph containment. They may also use an appropriate property of their choice — for example (a subproperty of) dcterms:hasPart — to link instances of dqv:QualityMetadata with instances of other DQV classes.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Represents quality metadata, it is defined to group quality certificates, policies, measurements and annotations under a named graph.
Represents a policy or agreement that is chiefly governed by data quality concerns.

Represents feedback that users have on the quality of datasets or distributions. Besides dqv:qualityAssessment, which is the motivation required by all quality annotations, one of the predefined instances of oa:Motivation should be indicated as motivation to distinguish among the different kinds of feedback, e.g., classifications, questions.

Refers to the resource (e.g., a dataset, a linkset, a graph, a set of triples) on which the quality measurement is performed. In the DQV context, this property is generally expected to be used in statements in which objects are instances of dcat:Dataset or dcat:Distribution.
Represents the expected data type for metric's observed value (e.g. xsd:boolean, xsd:double etc...)

Refers to a quality annotation. Quality annotation can be applied to any kind of resource, e.g., a dataset, a linkset, a graph, a set of triples. However, in the DQV context, this property is generally expected to be used in statements in which subjects are instances of dcat:Dataset or dcat:Distribution.

Refers to the performed quality measurements. Quality measurements can be performed to any kind of resource (e.g., a dataset, a linkset, a graph, a set of triples). However, in the DQV context, this property is generally expected to be used in statements in which subjects are instances of dcat:Dataset or dcat:Distribution.

Refers to a grouping of quality information such as certificates, policies, measurements and annotations as a named graph. Quality information represented in such a grouping can pertain to any kind of resource (e.g., a dataset, a linkset, a graph, a set of triples). However, in the DQV context, this property is generally expected to be used in statements in which subjects are instances of dcat:Dataset or dcat:Distribution.

http://purl.org/vocab/vann/usageNote.@value: Categories are meant to systematically organize dimensions. The Data Quality Vocabulary defines no specific cardinality constraints for dqv:inCategory, since distinct quality frameworks might have different perspectives over a dimension. A dimension may therefore be associated to more than one category. However, those who define new quality metrics should try to avoid this as much as possible and assign only one category to the dimensions they define.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Represents the category a dimension is grouped in.

http://purl.org/vocab/vann/usageNote.@value: Dimensions are meant to systematically organize metrics, quality certificates and quality annotations. The Data Quality Vocabulary defines no specific cardinality constraints for dqv:inDimension, since distinct quality frameworks might have different perspectives over a metric. A metric may therefore be associated to more than one dimension. However, those who define new quality metrics should try to avoid this as much as possible and assign only one dimension to the metrics they define. More than one dimension can be indicated for each quality annotation or certificate.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Represents the dimensions a quality metric, certificate and annotation allow a measurement of.
Indicates the metric being observed.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Precision is a quality dimension, which refers to the recorded level of details. It represents the exactness of a measurement or description. It is equivalent the notion of Precision from ISO 25012.

http://purl.org/vocab/vann/usageNote.@value: Whenever DQV implementers need to extend the motivations for quality annotations, they should follow the instructions provided by the Web Annotation Data Model, and the concepts in the extension should be defined as specializations of dqv:qualityAssessment.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Motivation that must be specified for quality annotations.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Refers to values computed by metric.
OAUTH2 via JWT
Message requesting an access token. This is intended for point-to-point communication with, e.g., Brokers.
Response to an access token request, intended for point-to-point communication.
A thing one might be permitted to do or prohibited from doing to something.
Something that occurs over a period of time and acts upon or with entities.
Internal or external Agent interacting with the Industrial Data Space, not necessarily an IDS Participant.
The class of documents describing an API or service contract in a complete and concise way so that it can act as a basis for developing or (automatically) inferring clients.
Secure platform for distributing Data Apps.
Instance of a Representation materialized at a partiuclar version and point in time. Possesses characteristics like file name, size, creation date etc.
Message indicating availability of a specific artifact.
Message asking for retrieving the specified Artifact as the payload of an ArtifactResponse message.
Message that follows up a RetrieveArtifact Message and contains the Artifact's data in the payload section.
Terminal data nodes, i.e. an atomic, possibly typed scalars.
Content intended for auditive perception, requires an audio output device (i.e. a loudspeaker) to present the contents.
Audio representation
Resource (at least partially) comprising audio content.
Holds authentication information so that connections to the Connector's data offerings can be establised.
The class of authentication standards that may be supported by Connectors.
Implementation of the Connector specification providing only restricted security capabilities.
The class of binary operators.
Defines an area of interest as a set of connected points.
Broker holding an index of published data endpoints.
Query command intended to be consumed by a Broker.
Class of scopes that may limit the space of broker query results.
e.g. Paypal, Visa Card
Class that aggregates Resources which, as a whole, form a (distributable) Catalog.
Abstract certification of compliance according to given Certification Scheme.

Appointed by the International Data Spaces Association the Certification Body manages the certification process, defines the standardized evaluation procedures and supervises the activities of the Evaluation Facilities.
Level of Certification
Scheme defining the processes, roles, targets, and criteria involved in the certification of components and entities; maintained by the Certification Body.
The product is subject to a fee-based use.
The Clearing House provides clearing and settlement services B2B interactions within the International Data Spaces.
Operation allowing the Client for custom pagination of underlying list.
Group of elements supporting particular access operations based on the concrete subclass.
Representation of a Collection, i.e. a Map or List of elements.
Resource comprising a set of named (Map) or ordered (List) elements.
Command messages are usually sent when a response is expected by the sender. Changes state on the recipient side. Therefore, commands are not 'safe' in the sense of REST.
Mutating operation that changes the internal state of the providing component.
Process and result of certifying a software component/servivce in order to become a certified part of the International Data Space infrastructure.
Level of a Component Certification
Resource comprising multiple Digital Contents.
Class of categories for classification of Resources.
Dedicated communication server for sending and receiving data in compliance with the Connector specification. There are different types of Connectors according to provided capabilities.
Event notifying the recipient(s) about the availability of a new connector. The payload of the message must contain the new connector's self-description.
Event notifying the recipient(s) about a connector's configuration change. The payload of the message must contain the updated connector's self-description.
Event notifying the recipient(s) that a connector will be temporarily unavailable and most likely be available again in the future.
Event notifying the recipient(s) that a connector will be unavailable and never be available again.
The class of Constraints that restrict a Rule.
Operation for receiving data via the operation’s input parameter(s) from the Data Provider to the Data Consumer.
The product is charged based on an effective consumption/demand (as opposed to a flat rate subscription).
Container composed of multiple (individually defined) parts.
Container representation, i.e. of a (compressed) archive.
Enumerated types of content expanding upon the Digital Content hierarchy.

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/usage.@value: Instances of Content Type are used to more precisely specify the type, genre or interpretation of a Digital Content.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Abstract set of rules governing the usage of a Resource.
Contract governing the actual usage of a Resource that has been agreed by all parties.
Message containing a contract with resource access modalities on which two parties have agreed.
Contract issued by the Data Provider offering the usage of a Resource at particular conditions.
Message containing a offered content contract (as offered by the data provider to the data consumer) in the associated payload (which is an instance of ContractOffer).
Message indicating rejection of a contract.
Contract issued by the Data Consumer requesting the usage of a Resource at particular conditions.
Message containing a suggested content contract (as offered by the data consumer to the data provider) in the associated payload (which is an instance of ContractRequest).
Activity with the goal to generate or produce an entity.
A selection of custom media types to be used for data published on the IDS when no IANA type is available.
Specialized security profile that is composed of user-defined security guarantees
The date (and optional time and timezone) of exercising the action of the Rule.
Custom or generic (semi)structured data intended for machine processing, i.e. atomic values or arrangements of data fields (optionally defined by a schema).

Self-contained, self-descriptive software package that is distributed via the App Store and deployed inside a Connector; provides access to data and data processing capa­bilities; the interface of a Data App is semantically described by the IDS Information Model.
Script code, algorithm or any other kind of interpreted software.

Add-on software extending a host Data App with a dedicated capability. The plugin depends on a particular version (range) of the host Data App which governs its integration, configuration and life-cycle.
Data App for a (stateless) processing of digital content according to exposed software interfaces.
Physical representation of (structured) data.
Resource (at least partially) comprising data content.
The class of datatypes for usage by Operation Parameters.
Entity described by a minimal textual annotation, i.e. a title and description.
Digital content of a particular type providing hints on its usage, e.g. listening to an Audio, navigating a Structure or accessing a List by an index.
The class of Duties as defined in the ODRL ontology.
Access point of data exchange and service interaction.
Evaluation Facilities carry out the evaluation work during a certification process and issue the corresponding Certifications.
Rules describing the relation and delivery of fault messages, i.e. whether they are omitted, replace or follow a regular operation message.
The product is charged based on a selection of features (i.e. map overlays, service set etc.)

Operation provides the Data Consumer with a selection of a Collection contents according to supplied Filter Parameter. The Filter is applied to 'structured' Resource content or file properties of Artifatcs (such as file extension, file name, file type, etc.).

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/rational.@value: Extends ids:ListContentOperation, since filtering upon entire Digital Contents which definition still applies.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Parameter holding a filter expression (matcher) used to identify a matching selection of contents.
The product is charged on subscription base independently of the actual consumption.
The product is free of charge, its usage is optionally restricted by non-financial constraints.
Model that exposes limited parts of the product at no cost, while additional parts are charged.
A location identified by a geonames URL.
A location identified by geo coordinates.
Geometrical shape indicating a spatial area of interest.
Network host capable of serving and consuming digital content and services.
The class of media types registered with IANA.

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/example.@value:
idsc_media:TEXT_CSV
        a ids:IANAMediaType;
        # the retrieved representation (HTML, turtle, RDF/XML) depends on content negotiation
        owl:sameAs <https://w3id.org/spar/mediatype/text/csv> .

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/usage.@value: Definition of an ids:IANAMediaType should define individual equivalence to corresponding SPAR-Media Type.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Parameter for conveying identifiers as defined by, e.g. an element collection (name/key). The identifier is unique and valid (in a defined context) regardless of the actual extent, ordering, and view (filtering).
The Identity Provider manages and validates the digital identity of International Data Spaces Participants.
Static content intended for visual perception/interpretation, requires a display device (i.e. a screen) to present the contents.
Image representation
Resource (at least partially) comprising image content.
Payment taking place immediately before or simultaneously to product consumption.

Parameter conveying the transient, positional identifier of a resource in the context of an ordered Collection. The resource index is temporarily unique and valid only with respect to the actual extent, ordering, and view (filtering) of the Collection.
The class of industries that can be distinguished by their activities.
Classification according to International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC).
The class of all infrastructure components of the IDS.
A temporal entity with zero extent or duration.
Endpoint exposing a digital content in a interacitve way.
Conceptualization of the interchange of digital artifacts as a set of uniform operations (interactions primitives).
A temporal entity with non-zero extent or duration, i.e. for which the value of the beginning and end are different.
Message requesting the recipient to invoke a specific operation.
Cryptographic Key Type.
The class of languages potentially being used by textual Data Assets.
Instances of the LeftOperand class are used as the leftOperand of a Constraint.
Class of Licences to be referred to by Resources.
Parameter indicating the number of elements retrieved or provided at once within a paginated subset (page).
Ordered collection of elements allowing for an index-based access.
Operation used by a Data Consumer to retrieve an enumeration of Collection's contents.

Operation used to retrieve the enumeration of available values for an 'Identifier' Parameter type. Depending on the type of underlying Resource collection, the identifier may be a unique name (map) or a numeric index (list); the Data Consumer may use the identifier for a subsequent call to 'Read' operation.
Operation exposing a list (ordered collection) of Digital Content.

Operation used by a (potential) Data Consumer to retrieve (a dynamically generated) enumeration of input parameter values (its enumerated value domain); suitable for use cases in which the complete parameter range cannot be specified beforehand.
Class of all locations on Earth.
The class of mutable individuals that are a potential subject to lifecycle management which may need to be tracked.
Collection of elements allowing for a key based access.
General class of media types (formerly known as MIME types).

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/usage.@value: ids:CustomMediaType is used only when no ids:IANAMediaType available.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Metadata describing payload exchanged by interacting Connectors.
Pattern governing the sequencing and cardinality of operation parameters.
Notification that a message has been successfully processed (i.e. not ignored or rejected).
Activity that sustainably modifies the managed entity, resulting in a new version.
Entity that is identifiable within a context by means of a name.
Event messages are informative and no response is expected by the sender.
Parameter indicating the absolute offset (number of data elements to skip) within an ordered data Collection. Negative values are bounded at Collections's end (reverse) index.
Opaque, not further specified type of custom, binary content.
Building block of an Interface; describes the interaction by defining input, output and error parameters.
Mapping of abstract operation signatures onto the concrete structures (e.g., HTTP headers or query parameters).
Message indicating that the result of a former InvokeOperation message is available. May transfer the result data in its associated payload section.
Enumerated types of operations expanding upon the Operation taxonomy.

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/usage.@value: Instances of Operation Type are used to more precisely specify the type, genre or interpretation of an Operation.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Parameter conveying the transient, positional identifier of a content page within a server-defined pagination.
Parameter conveying a relative reference to a content page within a server-defined pagination.
Named slot of an interface operation i.e., an input, output or fault (exception).
Expression of assigning a value to a parameter without creating an immediate reference.
Class of Parameters grouped according to an operator.
The class of operators that relate all members of a ParameterGroup.
Stakeholder in the Industrial Data Space, assuming one or more of the predefined roles; every participant is given a unique identity by the Identity Provider.
Whenever a Participant has been successfully certified by the Certification Body, the Identity Provider can use this message to notify Infrastructure Components.
Event notifying the recipient(s) that a Participant is temporarily no more certified.
Indicates that a (previously certified) Participant is no more certified. This could happen, for instance, if the Certification Body revokes a granted certificate or if the certificate just expires.
Process and result of certifying an interested party in order to become a certified member of the International Data Space.
Level of a Participant Certification

Event notifying the recipient(s) that information describing this Participant has changed. This event is mainly intended for information describing the Participant that is NOT a direct subject of the certification process.
Model considering the type and timing of the payment (the effective financial compensation).
The class of Permissions as defined in the ODRL ontology.
The class of persons (people)
The class of templates that describe a certain data usage policy.

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/usage.@value: Instances of this class conform to a certain textual representation which they need to indicate via a property.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Payment method requiring a contract allowing the product provider to charge the subscriber.
e.g. prepaid SIM
Overall commodization model composed of options.
Option of turning a Resource or Service into a product.
Operation for processing of digital content via operation’s IO parameter(s).
The class of Prohibitions as defined in the ODRL ontology.
Set of communication rules by which a Service implements its Interface(s) in order to become invocable.
Operation for providing a single Resource content via an operation’s output parameter from the Data Provider to the Data Consumer.
Activity with the goal to bring an entity into an operational state.
Public key as used in asymmetric cryptography.
Activity with the goal to make available an entity for public or restricted access.
The product is charged by instances of usage based on a particular metrics (byte size, number of API calls, ports etc.).
Class of query languages in which query strings may be formalized.
Query commands are intended to annotate query strings in a specified query language or address a specific resource.
Reading operation considered 'safe' by not affecting the state of the provising component.
Rejection messages are specialized response messages that notify the sender of a message that processing of this message has failed.
Class of reasons that might lead to issuing a Rejection message.
Activity with the goal to decommission an entity so that it can never be used anymore.
Syntactic template of a Resource.
A particular instance of given representation.
Notification that a request has been accepted and is being processed.
Client-generated message initiating a communication, motivated by a certain reason and with an answer expected.

Resource is a single digital content or a coherent set of digital contents. Resource content is formalized in Representations and optionally materialized as Artifacts. The Resource's content is exposed via defined Interfaces at various protocol Endpoints.
Parameter conveying a representation of resource's principal content, contrasted to parameters mediating arbitrary data.
Response messages hold information about the reaction of a recipient to a formerly sent command or event. They must be correlated to this message.
Result messages are intended to annotate the results of a query command.
Activity with the goal to resume operation of a temporarily suspended entity.
Superclass of Permissions, Prohibitions and Duties.
Resource (at least partially) comprising a Schema.
Security guarantee claimed by a security profile.
Set of security guarantees claimed by a Connector. Connectors may asses their mutual technical reliability and trustworthiness by evaluating each other’s security profile.
Operation provides the Data Consumer with custom fragments of the original Collection according to supplied 'Selector' Parameter. The Selector is applied to 'structured' Resource content.

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/rational.@value: Extends ids:QueryOperation, since content selection is driven by user-provided logic and can hardly be defined at description time

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Parameter holding a selector expression used to retrieve a subset of a Resource contents.
Message requesting the self-description of an Infrastructure Component.
Message containing the self-description of an Infrastructure Component.
Operation allowing the Client to navigate list content based on index of Server-defined sections.
Operation allowing the Client to navigate list content by references to Server-defined sections.
Activity with the goal to make an entity unoperational, while retaining it and make it operational again at a later point in time.
Resource comprising exactly one Digital Content.
An office or other premise at which the organization is located

Executable software (binary), interpreted program code (source) or fragments thereof. Intended purpose is an optional preprocessing (i.e. compilation, installation) and subsequnt execution/invokation of the software.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value: Term 'application' was misleading, since Mime Type of same name refers to unspecified data processed by some type of application program.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Software representation
Resource (at least partially) comprising Software.
Parameter indicating the keys underlying the sorting of an ordered Collection.
Class of possible order methods for collections.
Parameter indicating the sort direction of an ordered Collection.
Operation allowing for sorting of an underlying List.
Anything with spatial extent, i.e. size, shape, or position, e.g., places and unique positions.
Regulation mandated by a standardization body or set of rules established and followed by a community (de facto Standard).
Endpoint exposing  an Artifact.
Custom or standardized structured data
Payment taking on periodical rate according to underlying contract terms.
Activity with the goal to temporarily suspend operation of an entity.
Data Apps that integrate sources and sinks of digital content maintained internally on Participant's premises with a Connector.
A temporal interval or instant.
Informative textual content intended for reading and interpretation by humans and other intelligent agents. Comprises any digital representation of text, e.g. document and image (screenshot).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value: Text generlizes the notion of Media Type 'text' as a meaningful sequence of characters written in a set of human language(s), regardless of the formating and file type (e.g. plain, Word or PostScript).

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Representation of a textual content.
Resource (at least partially) comprising textual content.
A token (e.g., for authorization) mediated as part of the message.
Possible formats for (security-related) tokens.
Hardened implementation of the Connector specification providing enhanced security capabilities.
Generic class of units used with quantifiable properties.
Literal, inline value instantiation of a representation.
Dynamic content intended for visual and auditive perception, combines requirements of image and audio Content Types, while imposing further requirements on video decoding etc.
Video representation
Resource (at least partially) comprising video content.
Activity with the goal to withdraw public or restrict availability of an entity.
The allowed region of the consuming connector or Data App.
Access URL (e.g., http/websocket host, mqtt broker address and port) required for communication using the protocol.
The regular period with which items are added to a collection.
The operation relating to the asset for which permission is being granted.
Constraint that refines an Action.
Freetext description of what has been performed by the Activity.
and operator
Document describing the operations exposed by the endpoint.
Reference to a parameter assignment that describes how an artifact has been created.
The recipient of the policy statement.
The issuer of the policy statement.
Information of the authentication service used by the Connector.
The URL of the authentication service that is provided by the Connector.
The standard used by the authentication service that is provided by the Connector.
An authorization token like JSON Web Token.
References a new artifact from an availability indication.
The basic offered contract that the contract request message refers to.
Beginning of an Interval.
Operation bound to a particular protocol endpoint.
The scope of a query defined in a BrokerQuery message.
Size of the Artifact in bytes.
References the Catalog of published or requested resource by this Connector.
Level of certification (based on a combination of requierements, evaluation method etc.)
Checksum of the artifact
Certification issued for the given Infrastructure Component.
Reference to a Connector listed in the Broker.
The constraint to be used for a specific rule.
Consumer of a Resource or Service that is the subject matter of the Contract. This party may differ from the Assignee specified by the Contract rules.
Reference to a Digital Content (physically or logically) included, definition of part-whole hierarchies.
Constraint that refines a (composite) Digital Content.
Standards document defining the given Digital Content. The content is assumed to conform to that Standard.
Detailed type, genre or interpretation of the Digital Content.
Any type of resource related to the Contract.
Date of singing the Contract.
Equivalent human-readable encoding of this machine-interpretable Contract.
Date and time the Contract is requested, offered or expected to end. If omitted, the contract has to be explicitly terminated by any of the parties.
Reference to a Contract Offer defining the authorized use of the Resource.
Human-readable text describing the reason for contract rejection.
Date and time the Contract is requested, offered or expected to start, depending on the type of Contract.
Email address for contacting the participant on a general level.
General official homepage of the participant.
Correlated message, e.g. a response to a previous request.

https://w3id.org/idsa/metamodel/explanat.@value:
Definition of a Resource Endpoint is by purpose split into an address part (path, topic etc.)
and host information used to augment and resolve the address. Such the overall address space
is self-contained and may move across hosts. Further, changes of either component (address vs. host)
do not affect the other.
